## Goal

Implement rate limiting at the HTTP server layer (`libs/b3nd-servers/http.ts`) to prevent denial-of-service attacks against B3nd nodes. This is separate from protocol-level gas fees (Group 3) -- gas prevents economic spam within the protocol, while HTTP rate limiting prevents network-level abuse that could exhaust server resources before messages even reach the protocol layer. A node operator should be able to configure per-IP and per-endpoint rate limits.

## Background

The HTTP server in `libs/b3nd-servers/http.ts` uses the `MinimalRouter` interface (a lightweight Hono abstraction) to define routes:
- `POST /api/v1/receive` -- write endpoint (most abuse-prone)
- `GET /api/v1/read/:protocol/:domain/*` -- read endpoint
- `GET /api/v1/list/:protocol/:domain/*` -- list endpoint
- `DELETE /api/v1/delete/:protocol/:domain/*` -- delete endpoint
- `GET /api/v1/health` -- health check
- `GET /api/v1/schema` -- schema listing

The `httpServer()` function accepts a `MinimalRouter` and optional `HttpServerOptions` (currently only `healthMeta`). Rate limiting configuration would be added to these options.

The wallet server (`libs/b3nd-wallet-server/core.ts`) has its own Hono app and may get rate limiting in G5-A9-02. This story focuses specifically on the node-level HTTP server used by `b3nd-node`, which has no authentication layer and is publicly accessible.

Key considerations:
- **Per-IP tracking**: Use `X-Forwarded-For` or `X-Real-IP` header (behind reverse proxy) or connection IP
- **Sliding window**: Fixed window has burst issues at boundaries; sliding window is smoother
- **In-memory storage**: Production would ideally use Redis, but for portability and simplicity, in-memory with LRU eviction is the right starting point
- **Configurable limits**: Different endpoints need different limits (health: generous, receive: stricter)
- **Response format**: 429 status with `Retry-After` header and JSON error body

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `RateLimiter` class implemented with sliding window algorithm
- [ ] Rate limiter uses in-memory storage with configurable max entries and LRU eviction
- [ ] Rate limiting middleware added to `httpServer()` that wraps all routes
- [ ] IP extraction from `X-Forwarded-For`, `X-Real-IP`, or `CF-Connecting-IP` headers (configurable trust proxy setting)
- [ ] Per-endpoint-category limits: `receive` (writes), `read` (reads), `admin` (health, schema, metrics)
- [ ] Default limits: receive 60/min per IP, read 300/min per IP, admin 600/min per IP
- [ ] Limits configurable via `HttpServerOptions.rateLimits`
- [ ] Rate-limited responses return 429 with `Retry-After` header (seconds until window resets)
- [ ] Rate-limited responses return JSON body: `{ error: "Rate limit exceeded", retryAfter: N }`
- [ ] Rate limiter exposes current state for metrics integration (total limited count, active IPs)
- [ ] Allowlist support: specific IPs can bypass rate limiting (for trusted peers, monitoring)
- [ ] Rate limiter cleans up expired entries to prevent memory leaks (periodic eviction or LRU)
- [ ] Tests for rate limiting behavior: within limits, at limit, over limit, window reset, allowlist bypass

## Implementation Guide

1. Read `libs/b3nd-servers/http.ts` to understand the `httpServer()` function, `HttpServerOptions`, and the `MinimalRouter`/`MinimalContext` interfaces. Note how middleware would need to work with the minimal router (no Hono middleware support, must wrap route handlers).

2. Create `libs/b3nd-servers/rate-limiter.ts` with the sliding window rate limiter:
   ```typescript
   export interface RateLimitConfig {
     /** Requests allowed per window (default: 60) */
     maxRequests: number;
     /** Window duration in milliseconds (default: 60000 = 1 minute) */
     windowMs: number;
   }

   export interface HttpRateLimitOptions {
     /** Rate limits by endpoint category */
     receive?: RateLimitConfig;
     read?: RateLimitConfig;
     admin?: RateLimitConfig;
     /** Default limit for uncategorized endpoints */
     default?: RateLimitConfig;
     /** IPs that bypass rate limiting */
     allowlist?: string[];
     /** Trust proxy headers for IP extraction (default: false) */
     trustProxy?: boolean;
     /** Maximum number of tracked IPs before LRU eviction (default: 10000) */
     maxTrackedIps?: number;
   }

   export class SlidingWindowRateLimiter {
     private windows: Map<string, { timestamps: number[]; }>;
     private maxEntries: number;

     constructor(private config: RateLimitConfig, maxEntries = 10000) { ... }

     /** Check if request is allowed. Returns { allowed, remaining, resetMs } */
     check(key: string): { allowed: boolean; remaining: number; resetMs: number } { ... }

     /** Clean up expired entries */
     cleanup(): void { ... }
   }
   ```

3. The sliding window algorithm:
   - For each IP key, maintain an array of request timestamps
   - On each request, remove timestamps older than `windowMs`
   - If remaining timestamps count < `maxRequests`, allow and record timestamp
   - If at/over limit, reject with time until oldest timestamp expires

4. Implement IP extraction function:
   ```typescript
   function extractClientIp(request: MinimalContext, trustProxy: boolean): string {
     if (trustProxy) {
       // Check headers in priority order
       const cfIp = request.req.header("CF-Connecting-IP");
       if (cfIp) return cfIp;
       const realIp = request.req.header("X-Real-IP");
       if (realIp) return realIp;
       const forwardedFor = request.req.header("X-Forwarded-For");
       if (forwardedFor) return forwardedFor.split(",")[0].trim();
     }
     // Fall back to connection IP (available via Deno.serve connInfo)
     return "unknown";
   }
   ```

5. Implement endpoint categorization:
   ```typescript
   function categorizeEndpoint(method: string, path: string): "receive" | "read" | "admin" {
     if (path.startsWith("/api/v1/receive")) return "receive";
     if (path.startsWith("/api/v1/read") || path.startsWith("/api/v1/list")) return "read";
     return "admin"; // health, schema, metrics, delete
   }
   ```

6. Integrate into `httpServer()` in `libs/b3nd-servers/http.ts`:
   - Add `rateLimits?: HttpRateLimitOptions` to `HttpServerOptions`
   - Create rate limiter instances for each category in the `httpServer()` function
   - Since `MinimalRouter` doesn't support middleware natively, wrap route handlers:
     - Before each route handler executes, check rate limit
     - If limited, return 429 response directly
     - This can be done by wrapping the `app.get()` and `app.post()` calls with a rate-check function
   - Alternatively, add rate limiting as the first check inside each route handler

7. Set up periodic cleanup (every 60 seconds) to evict expired entries and enforce LRU if max entries exceeded.

8. Expose metrics integration point:
   ```typescript
   interface RateLimiterMetrics {
     totalLimited: number;
     activeIps: number;
     limitedByCategory: Record<string, number>;
   }
   ```

9. Update `HttpServerOptions` type and export from `libs/b3nd-servers/mod.ts`.

## Files to Create/Modify

- `libs/b3nd-servers/rate-limiter.ts` -- New file: `SlidingWindowRateLimiter`, `HttpRateLimitOptions`, IP extraction, endpoint categorization
- `libs/b3nd-servers/http.ts` -- Integrate rate limiting into route handlers, add `rateLimits` to `HttpServerOptions`
- `libs/b3nd-servers/mod.ts` -- Export rate limiter types and classes

## Testing

```bash
deno test libs/b3nd-servers/
```

Specific test scenarios:
- Requests within limit are allowed (remaining count decreases)
- Request at limit boundary is rejected with 429
- `Retry-After` header contains correct seconds until window resets
- Window reset allows new requests after waiting
- Different endpoint categories have independent limits
- Allowlisted IP bypasses rate limiting
- IP extraction from `X-Forwarded-For` works when `trustProxy` is true
- IP extraction ignores proxy headers when `trustProxy` is false
- LRU eviction removes oldest entries when `maxTrackedIps` exceeded
- Periodic cleanup removes expired entries
- Concurrent requests to same IP are handled correctly (no race conditions in counter)

Integration test:
```typescript
// Create a test server with low limits
const app = /* MinimalRouter */;
const server = httpServer(app, {
  rateLimits: {
    receive: { maxRequests: 3, windowMs: 1000 },
    read: { maxRequests: 10, windowMs: 1000 },
  }
});

// 3 receive requests succeed
// 4th receive request returns 429
// read requests still work (separate category)
```

## Dependencies

Depends on G5-E2-01 (monitoring/observability) for metrics integration. The rate limiter exposes metrics that the Prometheus endpoint from G5-E2-01 can scrape. Can be implemented independently but metrics integration requires G5-E2-01.
